agent:atlas:cron:47cfaf3a-ca98-4eb5-9851.task:
[cron:47cfaf3a-ca98-4eb5-9851-b12ee18641fa atlas-debug] Fix the enrichCronTokens function in portal/agents.html to properly show token data for crons that have been recreated with new UUIDs.

## Problem
When a cron job is recreated (new UUID), enrichCronTokens finds the most recent session_snapshot by last_seen_at. But the most recent session might be an empty placeholder (0 tokens) from the recreated cron. The actual work sessions ran under OLD UUIDs and have real token data (e.g. 422K tokens) but get ignored.

## Current code (around line 574-620 in agents.html)
```js
if (cronName && !tokenMap[cronName]) tokenMap[cronName] = r;
```
This keeps only the first (most recent) row per cron name. If that row is empty, you get 0K.

## Fix
Change the logic so that for each cron name, it keeps the most recent session that has MEANINGFUL token data (total_tokens > 1000). If no sessions have real data, fall back to the most recent one. This way, recreated crons still show their last real work.

Something like:
```js
if (cronName) {
  if (!tokenMap[cronName]) {
    tokenMap[cronName] = r;
  } else if (r.total_tokens > (tokenMap[cronName].total_tokens || 0) && (tokenMap[cronName].total_tokens || 0) < 1000) {
    // Replace empty/trivial entry with one that has real data
    tokenMap[cronName] = r;
  }
}
```

This must work for ALL crons, not just Atlas. Any cron that gets recreated should behave correctly.

## Also
The allRows query has .limit(200) on each of two queries. Increase to at least 500 each, or paginate, to ensure we find historical sessions.

## Files
Only edit portal/agents.html

